recordings.rmk: A lucky encounter with a Goldcrest that was in the vicinity of my hidden recorder.  The clip opens with two 'revving' bursts from a Blue tit. After a series of Goldcrest calls, the clip ends with drumming from a Great Spotted Woodpecker at 1:28 and 1:38.  IMPORTANT INFORMATION: On the xeno-canto sonogram that appears as a sample of the recording, the species whose sonogram appears is Blue Tit, not Goldcrest!  You can, however, see the full sonogram by going to the menu to the lower right of the sonogram display and looking for ACTIONS. At ACTIONS, select 'Download full-length sonogram'. Incidentally, it is always worth doing this for every recording - then you can follow the sound 'visually'.

recordings.rmk: Another clip from the Goldcrest that featured on XC550822. On this clip, other birds are equally well represented. Such as Chiffchaff at 0:01; 0:10; 0:17; 0:25; 0:33. Robin sings at 0:42; 0:47; 0:51; 0:57. A Blackcap can be heard in the background at 0:38. The Goldcrest gives an especially long song burst from 0:44 for a full eleven seconds. During this time, the Robin manages to sing twice!

recordings.loc: Ireland, Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk: Song recorded remotely by leaving the recorder among tall willow scrub and Elder trees. Although Goldcrest's  song bursts have a regular momentum and pattern, the final note in each series of cyclical notes is often not the same. Such as the final  note at 0:35, that has the quality of Long-tailed Tit's 'syrup' call ; whereas the concluding note at 0:56 is harder (almost finch-like) and the trill that ends just after 1:13 has no real closing flourish at all. Among the Goldcrest deliveries, you can hear a Blackcap that, to begin with, is lost against the Goldcrest's song bursts. However, the Blackcap can be better detected at 0:17; 0:23; 0:31; 0:47. A Chiffchaff sings at the beginning and also at 0:11; 0:37; 0:44.  A Wren sings at 1:08; 1:14; and from 1:25 to the end of the clip. A second recording of this bird is at XC550832.

I'm in the middle of a  pine trees coastal forest road in the middle of the afternoon, the weather is cloudy, there is no wind, the waves purr in the distance. A huge flock of 60+ goldcrests, 20+ firecrests and some blues tits crosses the road in flight just above me, continuing their migration route to the south.

I'm in the middle of a  pine trees coastal forest road in the middle of the afternoon, the weather is cloudy, there is no wind, the waves purr in the distance. A huge flock of 60+ goldcrests, 20+ firecrests and some blues tits come around me. The birds are foraging between 5 and 25 meters from me, constantly calling and moving. At the end of the track, the half of the group crosses the road, continuing their migration route, to the south.

recordings.loc: Augsburg, Siebentischwald, east of past Behringer Hof
recordings.rmk:
in mixed forest -- sound was trapped ...habi:'TANNE1-REWE'

----- i tryed to record sound of moult-time in the wood ...i fastened for that 4 days my recorder at a low branch of a spruce (the wind in the tree is sometimes stronger to hear, sorry) 

> when i was at this place at 22.07.17 morning... nearly the only birds i heard, were juv. Phylloscopus collybita with their adults - and there was strong calm of birds in the forest.

-- ....but when my recorder was alone in this habitat we hear quiet a lot of birds --and when in this seldom entered place... were people these days... the birds stopped singing and calling immediately for 1 hour and longer!

....>>> generally noted to moult: "The birds stop singing. Most birds already did, or sing infrequent. ---- Mating, nesting, breeding, feeding, caring. Exhausted. --- Renew worn plumage. --- Moult, fattening up for migration or the coming winter. ----

- No need, no energy, no time to sing.

Apart from silence, the only new sounds this time of year are those of juveniles and of some birds already returning from up north".
